snippet.textDisplay: Such a disappointment!  I'll reconsider next time before buying AMD. Now I truly wish I bought Intel back in 2017 (especially since a 7700K with liquid metal is still comparable to current high end RYZEN parts in gaming). Motherboard vendors can just remove support for older CPU's in the BIOS to free up space (they removed Bristol Ridge support to provide Zen2 support on my X370 motherboard). They also provided PCIe gen4 support until AMD took that away. So they supported 3 generations now which is only one more than Intel often does. Big f*cking deal. At least with Intel you know it won't have very long upgradeability so you don't expect it.

snippet.textDisplay:
The reason the whole B450/X470 thing is a kick in the pants is because they didn't tell anyone until now. Last year they said nothing about b450/x470 being the end of the line so a lot of people who were upgrading went with b450/x470 because who cares about x570's PCIE 4.0 and it has a tiny fan? and it's how much? No thank you. If we would have been informed about future lack of support when 3000 launched we all would have been able to make a more informed purchasing decision. 

We were all under the assumption we'd be fine until 2020 because THAT'S WHAT AMD TOLD US. This is a shitty move and they should rightly be shamed into reversing it. There are a lot of folks with b450/x470 boards and 3000 chips who are going WTF right now. Many more people would have certainly bought an x570 board if they knew b450/x470 was a dead end chipset.

snippet.textDisplay:
The Zen incompatibility isn't that big of a deal, since there is a massive upgrade path if you have a good enough b450 board (up to 16 Zen 2 cores), and the prices of those higher end CPUs is gonna drop after Zen 3 releases.

Im not saying it isn't greedy, but it isn't the end of the world either. As long as motherboard manufactures don't drop the ball on B550 designs (the majority of B450 boards had terrible VRM and CPU temperatures).
